Repositories, where packages come from.

Packages do not appear out of thin air; they come from repositories, which are servers hosting a catalog and the package files themselves. Your distribution ships with a default set of repositories already enabled, and you can add more when you need software that is not in them.

On the debian family, repositories are configured in the sources list under slash e-t-c slash apt, and in drop-in files beside it. A typical line names the type, the u-r-l of the server, the codename of your release, and a set of components. Those components carry meaning: main is officially supported free software, restricted holds proprietary drivers, universe is community-supported free software, and multiverse is proprietary software. To add a third-party repository, such as one for docker, you typically add the repository's signing key so that apt trusts it, add the source line in a drop-in file, refresh the catalog, and then install. On the red hat family, repositories are configured by i-n-i-style files in a yum-repos directory, and you enable, disable, or list them with the config-manager tool.

One concept underlies all of this and you must take it seriously: g-p-g signatures. Packages from real repositories are cryptographically signed with the repository's key, and your package manager verifies that signature before installing anything, which protects you against tampered packages served from a compromised mirror. Never ignore a signature error; either install the proper key from a source you trust, or do not install the package at all. Finally, on the red hat family there is a widely used extra repository called e-p-e-l, extra packages for enterprise linux, maintained by the fedora project, which adds a great many community packages that the conservative default repositories leave out.
